VALUES ('real-p-1772686723789', 'email', TRUE, 'hard', 'Robert Ashby <r.ashby@deltafreight-partners.com>', 'Last-mile routing update — Project Ironclad Phase 2 rollout', 'Hi Aisha,

We''re finally at the Phase 2 rollout milestone for Project Ironclad and I wanted to loop you in directly since you''ve been the primary contact on the last-mile optimisation piece from the start.

The routing algorithm update is scheduled to go live in the platform on the 14th. Before that happens, our integration team needs to validate the API token your team generated for the FourKites connection back in March — apparently there was a credential rotation on your side that our system didn''t pick up, and if we go live with the old token the live tracking feeds will break at cutover.

Could you log in through the integration management dashboard and re-confirm the FourKites API token? It''ll only take a moment — the dashboard is at: [integrations.deltafreight-partners.com/token-verify?project=ironclad-phase2](https://integrations.deltafreight-partners.com/token-verify?project=ironclad-phase2)

I''ve copied our integration lead, Chris Yuen, who''ll be monitoring the token validation from our side. Once the token is confirmed we''re clear for the 14th.

Thanks Aisha — this one''s been a long time coming and it''s good to be at the finish line.

Robert Ashby
Project Delivery Manager | Delta Freight Partners
[www.deltafreight-partrers.com](www.deltafreight-partrers.com)', 'hyper-personalization', 'null', null, null, null, null, ARRAY['["https://integrations.deltafreight-partners.com/token-verify?project=ironclad-phase2','re-confirm the FourKites API token','www.deltafreight-partrers.com"]']::TEXT[], ARRAY['["The link in the email body uses the domain ''deltafreight-partners.com''',' but the signature URL reveals the actual registered domain as ''deltafreight-partrers.com'' — ''partners'' is misspelled as ''partrers'' (transposed ''r''). The FROM address also uses ''deltafreight-partners.com''. This means the FROM domain is the lookalike and the signature accidentally reveals the attacker''s registered domain',' confirming neither matches a real company site the recipient would independently know.','Requesting API token credentials via an emailed link is not a legitimate integration validation process. Real API credential management happens within the platform''s authenticated admin console',' not through email-initiated portal links.','The project name (Project Ironclad)',' the named integration platform (FourKites)',' and the named colleague (Chris Yuen) create deep false credibility. The technical framing of a ''credential rotation'' is designed to make the token request feel like a routine infrastructure task rather than a credential harvest."]']::TEXT[], 'This is a hard phishing email targeting a logistics project manager at the completion milestone of a named project. The attacker references Project Ironclad Phase 2, a real last-mile visibility platform (FourKites), a plausible technical issue (API token rotation mismatch), and a named integration colleague. Every element is calibrated to read as authentic internal project coordination. The forensic tell is a domain transposition: the sender''s FROM domain is ''deltafreight-partners.com'', but the signature website is ''deltafreight-partrers.com'' — ''partners'' misspelled as ''partrers''. Comparing the two character by character reveals the discrepancy. The API token re-confirmation request is the credential harvesting mechanism dressed as a technical pre-launch task.', 'generated', 'v1')
ON CONFLICT (card_id) DO NOTHING;

