VALUES ('real-p-1772686644192', 'email', TRUE, 'easy', 'Aisha Brennan <aisha.brennan@trendharbour-staff.com>', 'Quick Note — Shift Schedule Update for You, Tom', 'Hi Tom,

Just a heads-up from the TrendHarbour store management team. We''ve updated the staff scheduling system and your upcoming shift assignments have changed for the next two weeks.

To view your new schedule and confirm your availability, you''ll need to log back into the employee portal using the link below. We migrated to a new system last weekend, so your old bookmark may not work.

[View My Updated Schedule](http://trendharbour-staff.com/employee-login)

Just enter your usual TrendHarbour employee credentials when prompted.

If you run into any trouble, the store manager can also help. The main TrendHarbour site is at www.trendharbour.com.

Thanks,
Aisha Brennan
Store Operations | TrendHarbour Retail
www.trendharbour.com', 'hyper-personalization', 'null', null, null, null, null, ARRAY['["trendharbour-staff.com','enter your usual TrendHarbour employee credentials when prompted','your old bookmark may not work"]']::TEXT[], ARRAY['["The FROM address uses trendharbour-staff.com',' while the email body and signature both reference the real company domain as trendharbour.com. The ''-staff'' suffix is a common attacker trick to make a domain look like an official subdomain.','Asking the recipient to enter their existing credentials at an unfamiliar login page is a credential-harvesting technique. Legitimate system migrations do not require employees to enter passwords on new',' unannounced URLs.','Telling the recipient that their old bookmark won''t work is a social engineering cue designed to stop them from navigating to the real site independently',' which would expose the fraud."]']::TEXT[], 'This phishing email impersonates a TrendHarbour store operations manager to steal employee login credentials. The attacker''s domain, trendharbour-staff.com, is designed to look like an internal staff portal subdomain, but it differs from the real domain trendharbour.com explicitly mentioned in both the signature and the body. The mild personalization (recipient''s first name, references to shift schedules and an employee portal) is just enough to seem plausible to a retail worker. The false claim about a system migration is used to justify the unfamiliar login link.', 'generated', 'v1')
ON CONFLICT (card_id) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO cards_real (card_id, type, is_phishing, difficulty, from_address, subject, body, technique, secondary_technique, grammar_quality, prose_fluency, personalization_level, contextual_coherence, highlights, clues, explanation, source_corpus, dataset_version)
VALUES ('real-p-1772686819156', 'email', TRUE, 'easy', 'Michael Torres <support@powerline-utilities.net>', 'Urgent: Update Your Account Credentials for Power Grid Maintenance', 'Hi Marcus,

We are conducting scheduled maintenance on our billing system this week and need to verify all customer accounts. To ensure your account remains active during this period, please click the link below and re-enter your login credentials immediately.

[Update Your Account](http://powerline-utilites.net/login)

This is a routine procedure and must be completed by end of business Friday. If you do not update your credentials, your service may be temporarily suspended.

Thanks,
Michael Torres
Powerline Utilities Support', 'pretexting', 'null', null, null, null, null, ARRAY['["Update Your Account','re-enter your login credentials immediately','your service may be temporarily suspended"]']::TEXT[], ARRAY['["The display text is generic and the URL is suspicious — powerline-utilites.net is misspelled (missing an ''s'' in ''utilities'') compared to the sender domain.','Urgent credential requests are a classic phishing tactic; legitimate utilities rarely require credentials via email.','Threats of service suspension create artificial pressure to comply without thinking."]']::TEXT[], 'This is a phishing email using pretexting. The attacker fabricates a routine billing system maintenance scenario to justify asking for credentials. The URL domain (powerline-utilites.net) contains a typo compared to the FROM domain (powerline-utilities.net), which is the key tell. The urgency and threat of service suspension are designed to bypass caution. A legitimate utility company would never request credentials via email link.', 'generated', 'v1')
ON CONFLICT (card_id) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO cards_real (card_id, type, is_phishing, difficulty, from_address, subject, body, technique, secondary_technique, grammar_quality, prose_fluency, personalization_level, contextual_coherence, highlights, clues, explanation, source_corpus, dataset_version)
VALUES ('real-p-1772686776756', 'email', TRUE, 'easy', 'Events Coordinator <events@paradisebay-vacations.net>', 'Wedding Venue Contract – Signature Required Urgently', 'Hi Keiko,

Thank you for choosing Paradise Bay Vacations for your wedding! We''re excited to host your celebration. I''ve attached the final venue contract for your review and signature.

Please sign the document and return it along with your full legal name, date of birth, and the credit card you''ll use for the $15,000 deposit. We need this back by tomorrow to hold your June date.

Also include your card''s expiration date and the three-digit security code so we can process the payment right away.

Looking forward to your big day!

Events Coordination, Paradise Bay Vacations', 'pretexting', 'null', null, null, null, null, ARRAY['["the credit card you''ll use for the $15','000 deposit','card''s expiration date and the three-digit security code"]']::TEXT[], ARRAY['["No legitimate business asks for full credit card details (expiration and CVV) via email — this is PCI-DSS noncompliant and a major red flag for fraud.','Combining urgency (tomorrow deadline) with a request for full payment card data is a classic phishing combination."]']::TEXT[], 'This is phishing using pretexting. The attacker creates an emotionally resonant scenario (wedding venue booking) and time pressure (tomorrow deadline) to justify requesting full credit card information, including the CVV. The sender domain (paradisebay-vacations.net) is a lookalike. Requesting the expiration date and security code in plain text is the giveaway — legitimate payment processors use secure payment gateways, never email.', 'generated', 'v1')
ON CONFLICT (card_id) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO cards_real (card_id, type, is_phishing, difficulty, from_address, subject, body, technique, secondary_technique, grammar_quality, prose_fluency, personalization_level, contextual_coherence, highlights, clues, explanation, source_corpus, dataset_version)
VALUES ('real-p-1772686782029', 'email', TRUE, 'hard', 'Cascade Freight Systems <noreply@cascadefreight-portal.com>', 'Action Required: Carrier Portal MFA Device Re-Enrolment by Friday', 'Hi Jennifer,

This is an automated notification from Cascade Freight Systems IT Security. Our records show your multi-factor authentication device registered to the Carrier Management Portal has not been re-validated since our security policy update in Q3. Per Policy SEC-09, all carrier portal accounts must complete MFA device re-enrolment by this Friday to maintain uninterrupted access to load boards, proof-of-delivery submissions, and invoice processing.

Failure to complete re-enrolment by the deadline will result in your account being placed in read-only mode, which will prevent you from accepting new loads or updating shipment statuses — we want to make sure your operations aren''t affected.

The re-enrolment process takes about three minutes. You''ll be asked to confirm your current login credentials and then pair a new authentication device using the QR code displayed after sign-in.

Begin re-enrolment here: [Cascade Freight MFA Portal](https://mfa.cascadefreight-portal.com/reenrol?account=jenniferw)

If you believe you''ve received this in error, please contact our carrier support team at [support@cascadefreightsystems.com](support@cascadefreightsystems.com) or visit our help centre at [cascadefreightsystems.com](cascadefreightsystems.com).

Regards,
IT Security Team
Cascade Freight Systems', 'credential-harvest', 'null', null, null, null, null, ARRAY['["https://mfa.cascadefreight-portal.com/reenrol?account=jenniferw','support@cascadefreightsystems.com','you''ll be asked to confirm your current login credentials"]']::TEXT[], ARRAY['["The MFA re-enrolment link points to cascadefreight-portal.com',' but the support contact email and the help centre reference both use cascadefreightsystems.com. The FROM address also uses the -portal.com lookalike. This domain split is the attacker''s fingerprint.','The body helpfully points to the real domain (cascadefreightsystems.com) for support',' which inadvertently reveals that the FROM domain and the link domain are imposters. Attackers often include a real-looking contact to build trust',' not realising it creates a traceable inconsistency.','Legitimate MFA re-enrolment never begins by asking you to ''confirm your current login credentials.'' Credential entry should only happen at a known',' bookmarked portal — not through an emailed link. This framing is a classic credential-harvest setup disguised as a security process."]']::TEXT[], 'This is a medium-hard credential-harvest phishing email targeting a carrier portal user at a fictional freight company. The MFA re-enrolment narrative is plausible and professionally written, but the domain discrepancy is clear on inspection: the FROM address and the re-enrolment link use cascadefreight-portal.com, while the support email and help centre URL inside the body both reference cascadefreightsystems.com. Additionally, asking a user to confirm login credentials as the first step of MFA re-enrolment is not a legitimate security practice.', 'generated', 'v1')
ON CONFLICT (card_id) DO NOTHING;

