VALUES ('real-p-1772686808780', 'email', TRUE, 'medium', 'James Riley <j.riley@nys-tax-audit.gov>', 'Annual Compliance Review – Documentation Request', 'Dear Jennifer,

This letter is in regard to the annual tax compliance review for Riverside County Hospital, which is scheduled to conclude by November 15th. Your organization has been selected for a standard audit verification under the New York State Fiscal Accountability Act.

We have prepared a secure questionnaire that captures key financial documentation requirements. The form includes questions about your current accounting software, employee payroll systems, and bank reconciliation procedures — all standard items we verify during these reviews.

To complete your portion of this audit efficiently, please access the form here: [NYS Tax Compliance Form](https://secure-nys-tax-gov.com/audit/form?ref=RC-Hospital-2024). Use the temporary access code provided below to log in. Once you complete and submit the form, it will be flagged as reviewed in our central system and you''ll receive a confirmation receipt.

Temporary access code: RCHOSP-89742-AUDIT

Please complete this by November 10th to avoid any delays to your compliance status. If you have questions about the audit, you can reach our office at the number below.

Thank you,
James Riley
Tax Compliance Auditor
New York State Department of Taxation and Finance
www.tax.ny.gov
Phone: (518) 555-0147', 'pretexting', 'null', null, null, null, null, ARRAY['["access the form here','Use the temporary access code provided','secure-nys-tax-gov.com','www.tax.ny.gov"]']::TEXT[], ARRAY['["The FROM domain (nys-tax-audit.gov) appears official but the URL in the body uses secure-nys-tax-gov.com — the attacker has registered a lookalike .com domain instead of the legitimate .gov referenced in the signature','Temporary access codes and form-based requests are common phishing hooks; combined with the domain mismatch',' this is a credential harvesting attempt disguised as compliance documentation','The pretext uses regulatory authority and threat of compliance penalties to create urgency and discourage verification','The URL displays as a legitimate-sounding path (secure-nys-tax-gov.com/audit/form) to appear official',' but the domain itself is spoofed"]']::TEXT[], 'This is a medium-difficulty pretexting phishing email targeting a hospital administrator. The attacker establishes a highly plausible pretext: a government tax audit is a realistic and expected event, the referenced act name sounds official, and the request for financial documentation aligns with genuine audit procedures. The sender role (tax auditor) and organisation (NYS Tax Department) are credible. The ask — accessing a form to provide system and financial information — follows naturally from the pretext and would not immediately alarm a hospital finance officer. However, the forensic tell is the domain mismatch: the FROM address uses nys-tax-audit.gov, the signature references www.tax.ny.gov, but the form URL uses secure-nys-tax-gov.com (a registered lookalike with .com instead of .gov). A player focusing on the scenario and urgency language will miss the attack. A player comparing domains will spot the inconsistency and recognise the form as a credential harvesting page.', 'generated', 'v1')
ON CONFLICT (card_id) DO NOTHING;

