VALUES ('real-p-1772686793819', 'email', TRUE, 'hard', 'Keiko Sato <k.sato@harborpoint-claims.net>', 'ClaimsPro Upgrade — Session Token Migration for Active Adjusters', 'Hi Nadia,

The ClaimsPro system upgrade we''ve been rolling out over the past two weeks has reached the final phase — session token migration for active adjusters. Your account is included in this phase because you have open assignments in the catastrophe response queue.

What this step does is replace the legacy session architecture with the new persistent token model, which is what allows the mobile adjuster app to stay synced with your desktop queue without requiring repeated logins in the field. The migration happens silently in the background once you authenticate through the migration endpoint — you won''t notice any change to your workflow afterward.

The IT team has asked that adjusters on active CAT assignments complete this by end of day Wednesday to avoid any interruption to the claims sync during the overnight batch processing window. If your session token isn''t migrated before then, your mobile app will lose sync with the desktop queue until IT can manually reissue a token, which is a slower process.

To initiate the migration, just sign in at the link below with your standard ClaimsPro credentials:

[ClaimsPro Session Migration — Adjuster Sign-In](https://claimspro-migrate.harborpoint-claims.net/adjuster-token?id=nsullivan&phase=3)

If you have trouble with the link, email the ClaimsPro admin team at claimspro@harborpointclaims.com or call the internal support line at ext. 3302.

Thanks for getting this done, Nadia — the CAT team really appreciates how on top of things you''ve been this season.

Keiko Sato
Claims Systems Administrator | Harbor Point Claims
harborpointclaims.com', 'credential-harvest', 'null', null, null, null, null, ARRAY['["claimspro-migrate.harborpoint-claims.net/adjuster-token','claimspro@harborpointclaims.com','just sign in at the link below with your standard ClaimsPro credentials"]']::TEXT[], ARRAY['["The migration link uses the domain harborpoint-claims.net — matching the FROM address — while the ClaimsPro admin email and the footer signature both show the real company domain is harborpointclaims.com. The hyphen and the .net TLD are both lookalike modifications.','The ClaimsPro admin contact email in the body uses harborpointclaims.com',' directly contradicting the FROM domain of harborpoint-claims.net. This internal reference is the forensic anchor that exposes the mismatch.','The instruction to ''just sign in with your standard credentials'' at a migration endpoint is a classic credential-harvest framing — legitimate system token migrations are handled server-side and never require users to authenticate through an email link."]']::TEXT[], 'This hard credential-harvest email impersonates a Claims Systems Administrator at a fictional property and casualty insurance firm. The pretext — session token migration for catastrophe response adjusters during an active CAT event — is operationally specific and time-pressured in a way that would feel urgent and real to an insurance adjuster. The technical explanation of ''persistent token model'' and ''overnight batch processing'' adds plausible depth. The two tells are the FROM domain (harborpoint-claims.net vs. harborpointclaims.com) and the fact that the real domain appears in the body''s admin contact email, creating a directly comparable mismatch for a careful reader.', 'generated', 'v1')
ON CONFLICT (card_id) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO cards_real (card_id, type, is_phishing, difficulty, from_address, subject, body, technique, secondary_technique, grammar_quality, prose_fluency, personalization_level, contextual_coherence, highlights, clues, explanation, source_corpus, dataset_version)
VALUES ('real-p-1772682186076', 'email', TRUE, 'hard', 'Professor Sarah Chen <s.chen@westfield-college.org>', 'Grant Resubmission - NSF CAREER Award - Signature Required', 'David,

I hope the department retreat was useful. I wanted to reach out directly about the NSF CAREER resubmission — as you know, our first attempt was rejected on methodological grounds, and the program officer''s feedback was pretty clear about what needs to change.

I''ve incorporated the revisions with help from the graduate students, and Thomas from the chemistry department has signed off on the analytical approach. The final submission window closes Friday at 5 PM Eastern, and I need your signature on the budget justification form before I can upload it to the grants portal.

Could you log in to your FastGrants account and approve the budget revision? Here''s the direct link: [FastGrants Portal - Budget Approval](https://fastgrants-research.secure-review.net/login)

I know you''re busy, but this is our third cycle, and if we don''t submit by Friday, we''re locked out for another year. I''ve done the heavy lifting — I just need your institutional sign-off as PI on the budget line items.

Thanks for everything this semester. Let''s grab coffee and debrief on the revision strategy once this is submitted.

Sarah
Professor of Chemistry
[westfieldcollege.org](westfieldcollege.org) | Department of Chemistry & Biochemistry', 'hyper-personalization', 'null', null, null, null, null, ARRAY['["FastGrants account and approve the budget revision','https://fastgrants-research.secure-review.net/login','log in to your FastGrants account"]']::TEXT[], ARRAY['["Request to log in to a financial system (FastGrants) is framed as routine institutional business',' but the actual link domain (secure-review.net) does not match the legitimate system''s domain.','The link uses a plausible-sounding subdomain (fastgrants-research) combined with a fraudulent top-level domain',' designed to appear legitimate at a glance.','The personalization (mentioning the department retreat',' Thomas from chemistry',' third funding cycle',' and the program officer''s feedback) creates urgency and establishes the sender''s credibility',' making the credential request feel proportionate and necessary."]']::TEXT[], 'This is a hard hyper-personalization phishing attack targeting academic grant administration. The attacker has researched the recipient''s role as PI on an NSF CAREER resubmission, mentioned specific details (program officer feedback, graduate students, collaborator Thomas, three-cycle history, the Friday deadline) that would only be known to someone genuinely involved in this project. The phishing ask is a login request to FastGrants, the university''s legitimate grant management system. The FROM domain appears to be s.chen@westfield-college.org, but the signature references westfieldcollege.org (missing ''org'' in the FROM domain — the lookalike is westfield-college.org). The malicious link uses secure-review.net instead of the real FastGrants domain. The personalization establishes urgency and credibility, making it extremely likely the recipient will click the link and enter credentials. The attacker would gain access to the recipient''s grant management account and potentially the institution''s research funding data.', 'generated', 'v1')
ON CONFLICT (card_id) DO NOTHING;

