VALUES ('real-p-1772686813598', 'email', TRUE, 'hard', 'Kevin Ashworth <k.ashworth@solarisspecialty-ins.com>', 'E&O Coverage Renewal – Carrier Document Upload Required', 'Jennifer,

Our records show that your errors and omissions policy with Solaris Specialty is due for renewal on April 15th, and the underwriting team has asked me to reach out directly given that we''re now inside the 30-day window.

This year, the carrier is requiring all renewing agents to upload a completed professional liability questionnaire through the document portal before the renewal can be bound. It''s a new step introduced for the 2025 policy year — most agents are finding it takes about ten minutes. The questionnaire covers your current book composition, any claims activity in the past 36 months, and a short attestation regarding your E&O compliance training.

You can access the upload portal using the link below. Sign in with the email address associated with your Solaris account and you''ll land directly on the renewal checklist for your policy.

[Access the Solaris renewal document portal](https://solarisspecialty-ins.net/portal/renewal?policy=EOJA-2241-JF)

If we don''t receive the completed questionnaire by April 8th, the underwriting team may not have sufficient time to bind coverage before the expiry date, which could result in a gap. I want to make sure we get this wrapped up well in advance so that doesn''t become an issue for you.

Feel free to call me directly if you have any questions — my direct line is +1 312 555 0174.

Best,
Kevin Ashworth
Renewal Specialist | Solaris Specialty Insurance
www.solarisspecialty-ins.com', 'fluent-prose', 'null', null, null, null, null, ARRAY['["solarisspecialty-ins.net/portal/renewal?policy=EOJA-2241-JF','www.solarisspecialty-ins.com','If we don''t receive the completed questionnaire by April 8th',' the underwriting team may not have sufficient time to bind coverage before the expiry date"]']::TEXT[], ARRAY['["The renewal portal link uses the .net TLD',' while the company''s stated domain in the signature is solarisspecialty-ins.com. A single TLD substitution is the sole domain-level tell — everything else about the URL structure looks institutional and credible.','The FROM address and the body signature both confirm the legitimate domain ends in .com. Comparing the link''s .net domain against the .com domain in the signature is the forensic check that reveals this email as phishing.','The coverage-gap warning (''may not have sufficient time to bind coverage before the expiry date'') introduces time pressure calibrated to feel like professional concern rather than urgency. This is a hallmark of fluent-prose phishing — the stakes are framed as consequences',' not threats."]']::TEXT[], 'This is a hard phishing email targeting an insurance agent''s E&O renewal, a high-stakes annual process that agents are conditioned to take seriously. The language is measured and professional, and the threat of a coverage gap serves as the pressure mechanism without sounding alarming. The only technical tell is the TLD discrepancy in the portal link (.net vs. the legitimate .com). The policy number in the URL (EOJA-2241-JF) adds authenticity and discourages second-guessing. A player relying on tone or grammar will find nothing suspicious — only URL inspection catches it.', 'generated', 'v1')
ON CONFLICT (card_id) DO NOTHING;

INSERT INTO cards_real (card_id, type, is_phishing, difficulty, from_address, subject, body, technique, secondary_technique, grammar_quality, prose_fluency, personalization_level, contextual_coherence, highlights, clues, explanation, source_corpus, dataset_version)
VALUES ('real-p-1772682065987', 'email', TRUE, 'easy', 'Benefits Administration <benefits@federal-employee-hhs.net>', 'Action Required: Verify Your Federal Benefits Portal Login', 'Dear Jennifer,

We have detected unusual activity on your Federal Employee Benefits account. As a precaution, we have restricted access to your profile until your identity is confirmed.

Please click the link below to log in and verify your account details:

[https://federal-employee-hhs.net/login-verify](https://federal-employee-hhs.net/login-verify)

You will be asked to enter your username and password. Once verified, full access to your benefits selections, open enrollment options, and direct deposit settings will be restored.

Failure to complete this step within 48 hours will result in your open enrollment selections being cancelled for the current benefits year.

Regards,
Federal Employee Benefits Administration
Official portal: [www.federalemployeebenefits.hhs.gov](www.federalemployeebenefits.hhs.gov)', 'credential-harvest', 'null', null, null, null, null, ARRAY['["We have detected unusual activity','https://federal-employee-hhs.net/login-verify','enter your username and password','your open enrollment selections being cancelled"]']::TEXT[], ARRAY['["''Unusual activity detected'' is one of the most common pretexts used in phishing emails — it creates alarm without providing any verifiable details.','The sender''s domain is federal-employee-hhs.net',' but the official portal listed in the signature is federalemployeebenefits.hhs.gov — a real U.S. government site would use a .gov domain',' not .net.','Asking you to enter your username and password via a link in an email is the definition of credential harvesting — this step would never appear in a legitimate benefits verification process.','Threatening cancellation of health benefits enrollment creates extreme personal urgency',' a manipulation technique designed to make recipients act without thinking."]']::TEXT[], 'This phishing email impersonates a federal employee benefits administration office. The domain mismatch is decisive: the email comes from federal-employee-hhs.net, while legitimate U.S. government services exclusively use .gov domains, as confirmed by the signature''s reference to federalemployeebenefits.hhs.gov. The email explicitly asks the recipient to enter credentials through a link — a textbook credential-harvest — and leverages fear of losing health benefits to drive panicked compliance.', 'generated', 'v1')
ON CONFLICT (card_id) DO NOTHING;

