VALUES ('real-l-1772686617977', 'email', FALSE, 'medium', 'Property Tax Assessment <notifications@county-assessor.gov>', 'Property Tax Bill 2024 – Ready for Viewing', 'Jennifer,

Your 2024 property tax bill has been prepared and is now available for viewing in your account. This is a notification that your bill is ready; no payment is due until April 30, 2024.

Property Details:
Parcel ID: 123-456-789-00
Address: 427 Maple Street, Springfield, County
Assessed Value: $385,000
Total Tax Amount: $6,240.00
Bill Issue Date: March 1, 2024
Payment Due: April 30, 2024

You can view, print, and pay your bill anytime by logging into your property tax account at county-assessor.gov using your parcel ID and PIN. If you have made recent improvements to your property, you may request a reassessment review through your account portal.

Payment options include online credit/debit card (2% processing fee), bank transfer, or by mailed check. All payments must be received by the due date to avoid late penalties.

If you have questions about your assessment or believe there is an error, you have 30 days from the bill issue date to file an appeal. Appeal forms and instructions are available on our website.

Best regards,
County Assessor''s Office
Property Tax Administration
Phone: (555) 234-5678 | Website: county-assessor.gov | Email: assessor-support@county-assessor.gov', NULL, 'null', null, null, null, null, ARRAY['["Parcel ID: 123-456-789-00','Total Tax Amount: $6','240.00','Payment Due: April 30',' 2024','you have 30 days from the bill issue date to file an appeal"]']::TEXT[], ARRAY['["Government parcel IDs follow strict formatting standards; this specific numeric structure is verifiable against county records and would be known to the recipient.','Exact dollar amounts for taxes are deterministic and tied to assessed property value; attackers do not know these figures and would use vague language or round numbers.','A clear',' specific payment deadline with reference to late penalties is typical of official tax correspondence; phishing emails often use false urgency without concrete dates.','Mention of legal rights (appeal period',' reassessment request) is a hallmark of official government notices; scammers avoid providing legitimate procedural information."]']::TEXT[], 'This is a legitimate property tax bill notification from a county assessor''s office. The email includes all the substantive elements expected in official tax correspondence: a specific parcel ID tied to a real property address, an exact assessed value and tax amount, clear payment dates with a policy reference (appeal period), and multiple legitimate contact methods. The sender domain (county-assessor.gov) is plausible for a government agency, and the email provides no credential requests or suspicious links—only a reference to logging into an existing account the recipient would have created. A player might worry because it mentions financial information and requires action (payment), but the combination of verifiable property details, a reasonable timeline (60 days before due date), and formal procedural language confirms this as legitimate automated tax administration.', 'generated', 'v1')
ON CONFLICT (card_id) DO NOTHING;
